WHEREAS, Dr. Coreil championed workforce-aligned academic innovation by
supporting the expansion of Professional Aviation, Accountants for the Future, Educators
Rising, the Interdisciplinary Pre-Med program, the LEAD V program, and a 3+3
Occupational Therapy pathway with LSU Health Shreveport; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Coreil also advanced the development of a Health Education
Campus designed to expand nursing and allied-health training in central Louisiana, helping
address critical workforce shortages in the region; and
WHEREAS, under his watch, LSUA and the LSU System moved forward with
Louisiana's first three-year accelerated bachelor's degrees in STEM fields, including
Information Technology and Bioinformatics, demonstrating a forward-looking model of
workforce-aligned undergraduate education; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Coreil's administration also oversaw the completion of key campus
projects, including the Martin Family Student Success Center, which stands as a lasting
investment in student access, support, and success; and
WHEREAS, during his tenure, LSUA gained increasing statewide and national
recognition, including ranking as the number one safest college campus in Louisiana and the
number seven safest college campus in America by Niche, and rising to number four in
Niche's 2025 Best Colleges in Louisiana rankings; and
WHEREAS, before his chancellorship, Dr. Coreil served with distinction as Vice
Chancellor of the LSU AgCenter and Director of the Louisiana Cooperative Extension
Service from 2001 until 2013, following an earlier career that began as a Sea Grant agent in
Cameron and Calcasieu parishes; and
WHEREAS, one of Dr. Coreil's most significant accomplishments in that role was
his work in wetland resources, where he helped private landowners, industry, and
government agencies implement strategies to slow coastal land loss and served as a trusted
liaison in matters of environmental stewardship and public policy; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Coreil also made a profound and lasting contribution to youth
development through Louisiana 4-H, where over the course of thirty-four years he helped
strengthen the program, establish conservation initiatives such as Marsh Maneuvers, and
continue fundraising support for youth environmental programs even after retirement; and
